WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.480
Thanks, Daniel. Thank you for that introduction. Good morning,

00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:08.760
everyone. Happy to be here at PositConf and excited to talk to

00:00:08.760 --> 00:00:12.240
you a little bit about some of the unspoken realities of a data

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:17.040
science career. So to start, since we're all data people, I

00:00:17.040 --> 00:00:21.000
figured why not look at the data. So today I've pulled

00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:26.040
together some highly researched data on what makes a person have

00:00:26.040 --> 00:00:32.320
a successful and satisfied career. So this is my own

00:00:32.560 --> 00:00:37.799
personal experience. For me, I'm more of an introvert. I don't

00:00:37.799 --> 00:00:42.639
like asking questions if I don't have to. And I just much prefer

00:00:42.639 --> 00:00:45.720
figuring things out on my own. So for example, I love escape

00:00:45.720 --> 00:00:48.840
rooms, where you have to solve different puzzles to be able to

00:00:48.840 --> 00:00:52.720
escape. And I'm the person that will look through every nook and

00:00:52.720 --> 00:00:55.240
cranny in the room to try to figure out what's going on

00:00:55.720 --> 00:00:59.279
before I asked for a hint. So for me, flying solo just comes

00:00:59.279 --> 00:01:04.800
naturally. But I've learned I've been in industry just for over a

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:07.839
year, so I'm still new to my career. But I've had great

00:01:07.839 --> 00:01:11.440
mentors, and I've been able to talk to lots of people and learn

00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:16.440
better ways of navigating my data science career. And some of

00:01:16.440 --> 00:01:19.959
them were unexpected to me that I didn't know coming out of

00:01:19.959 --> 00:01:22.519
school what it would be like and there were some unexpected

00:01:22.519 --> 00:01:25.480
realities. And so today I'm going to talk to you about three

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:28.480
of these, expanding your network, finding your niche and

00:01:28.480 --> 00:01:33.680
advocating for yourself. So to start expanding your network,

00:01:33.760 --> 00:01:36.599
and when I was in my first internship, I would hear the

00:01:36.599 --> 00:01:41.360
word networking and I would cringe because I, like I said,

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:44.000
I'm more of an introvert and networking doesn't come easy to

00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.559
me talking to different people about their career aspects and

00:01:48.559 --> 00:01:51.360
career journeys was not something that was natural for

00:01:51.360 --> 00:01:55.879
me. But expanding your network is so much more than that. It's

00:01:56.080 --> 00:01:59.519
finding your people, it's finding resources in your

00:01:59.519 --> 00:02:04.680
company, in the community that you can ask questions to that

00:02:04.680 --> 00:02:08.199
can be there for for help. And also, it's about finding

00:02:08.199 --> 00:02:11.399
friends, finding friends at work and finding those that you

00:02:11.399 --> 00:02:16.160
really enjoy spending time with. And I learned this lesson at my

00:02:16.199 --> 00:02:20.399
first internship. So I had an internship between the junior

00:02:20.399 --> 00:02:23.520
and senior year of my undergrad, where I traveled across

00:02:23.520 --> 00:02:26.160
the country, I really was excited to work on this project

00:02:26.160 --> 00:02:29.160
and be a part of this intern program, where I was able to

00:02:29.160 --> 00:02:32.679
actually start Shiny. So I learned how to do a Shiny app

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:36.919
and was really excited to dive into this and be able to produce

00:02:36.960 --> 00:02:40.199
a good product for the company. So I really focused on that and

00:02:40.199 --> 00:02:43.440
focused on learning this new skill and working on this

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:46.360
project. But there were so many other interns there that I was

00:02:46.360 --> 00:02:49.839
able to meet. And there was one intern in particular that met

00:02:49.839 --> 00:02:53.759
with me during the internship, that he asked me some questions

00:02:53.759 --> 00:02:57.360
about my project about my career aspirations, what I was doing in

00:02:57.360 --> 00:03:01.559
school, and just got to know me on a more personal level. Later

00:03:01.559 --> 00:03:04.399
in the internship, we had our final presentations, and I went

00:03:04.399 --> 00:03:07.960
to his and he talked about his project that he worked on, but

00:03:07.960 --> 00:03:10.759
also all of the different people that he had met with over the

00:03:10.759 --> 00:03:13.880
course of the internship, internship, both interns and

00:03:13.880 --> 00:03:17.119
full time employees alike. He asked them questions like, what

00:03:17.119 --> 00:03:20.440
do you like about your job? What do you not enjoy? What are

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:24.479
some career opportunities for me? Or what is your career

00:03:24.479 --> 00:03:28.600
journey like? And he really was able to gain so many more

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:32.839
insights, I felt like and I really felt like I'd missed out

00:03:32.839 --> 00:03:37.800
on an opportunity to really get more insights from the people

00:03:37.800 --> 00:03:41.800
around me. And so a couple years later, I had another internship

00:03:41.839 --> 00:03:45.679
between in the summer between my first and second year of grad

00:03:45.679 --> 00:03:49.479
school. So I decided to try to prioritize more of my time in

00:03:49.479 --> 00:03:52.759
this internship while working on my project, to also put time

00:03:52.759 --> 00:03:56.320
into meeting others, and getting to know them and also asking

00:03:56.320 --> 00:03:58.759
questions about what they do, what they like about their job.

00:03:58.759 --> 00:04:00.960
And I talked to different data scientists, analysts,

00:04:01.199 --> 00:04:05.160
biostatisticians around the around the organization, to

00:04:05.360 --> 00:04:08.119
basically get some career advice for them and figure out if the

00:04:08.119 --> 00:04:11.080
company was a good fit for me. And by the end of this

00:04:11.080 --> 00:04:15.520
experience, I had gained so many resources around me that I was

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:19.000
able to say hi to people in the halls. And I was able to have

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:22.480
people to ask questions to and really, I actually ended up with

00:04:22.480 --> 00:04:25.200
more friends from this internship, and more people that

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:29.480
I could keep in contact with. So how might you expand your

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:33.880
network? And for me, it comes down to setting little goals.

00:04:33.959 --> 00:04:38.160
Maybe it's talking to someone in a coffee chat, maybe it's

00:04:38.160 --> 00:04:43.040
virtual or in person, depending on your work style. But me

00:04:43.040 --> 00:04:46.160
asking them about their career journey about what they like,

00:04:46.200 --> 00:04:50.480
what they don't like about their jobs, and maybe just getting to

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:53.959
know each other on a personal level. You may attend an

00:04:54.119 --> 00:04:58.959
after-work events or a social or join a club at work if there

00:04:58.959 --> 00:05:02.079
are those or employee resource groups. For me, I've been very

00:05:02.079 --> 00:05:05.000
fortunate enough to join an employee resource group at my

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:08.640
company and be on the committee for that group. So I've been

00:05:08.640 --> 00:05:11.040
able to help organize events and get to know colleagues that I

00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:14.399
wouldn't have been able to meet otherwise. And it's been an

00:05:14.399 --> 00:05:17.239
enriching experience where I've had incredible opportunities

00:05:17.239 --> 00:05:21.119
from it. Or if you don't have these opportunities at work, you

00:05:21.119 --> 00:05:24.480
might find the online communities or groups to join.

00:05:24.480 --> 00:05:27.440
And I mean, we're here at Posit.com, there are so many

00:05:27.679 --> 00:05:32.079
different opportunities and groups that meet and so many

00:05:32.079 --> 00:05:36.359
different ways to get to know others. And so this might be

00:05:36.359 --> 00:05:41.640
another opportunity for you. But remember, it gets easier

00:05:41.679 --> 00:05:44.480
every time you do it. So if you set a little goal to maybe do

00:05:44.480 --> 00:05:48.239
one coffee chat a month or go to an event and talk to one new

00:05:48.239 --> 00:05:52.279
person, every time you do it, it will get easier and it'll be

00:05:52.279 --> 00:05:57.640
more natural for you to do. So the second point that I wanted

00:05:57.640 --> 00:06:01.040
to talk about today is finding your niche. And this is finding

00:06:01.040 --> 00:06:04.519
your passion, finding what you enjoy doing and what makes you

00:06:04.519 --> 00:06:08.359
tick. And when I was thinking about this, I really like

00:06:08.359 --> 00:06:13.519
basketball and the NBA. And in the NBA, there is a term called

00:06:13.519 --> 00:06:17.920
the role player. So a team may have different role players that

00:06:18.959 --> 00:06:21.640
do different aspects of the team. And so there could be

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:24.320
three point shooters, you could have a person that's very good

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:28.799
at defense, and the teams will have different roles to support

00:06:28.799 --> 00:06:32.040
the superstars. So one ultimate role player that I can think of

00:06:32.040 --> 00:06:35.959
is Draymond Green. And Draymond Green plays for the Golden State

00:06:35.959 --> 00:06:39.079
Warriors, which I'm a Celtics fan. So it's not super fun to

00:06:39.079 --> 00:06:41.920
talk about Draymond Green, but he is very, a very good example

00:06:41.920 --> 00:06:46.559
of this where he really helps those around him score. And

00:06:46.760 --> 00:06:51.600
really, his main niche is to be a vocal leader and an energizer

00:06:51.600 --> 00:06:54.880
for the team. And so the team, the other players on the team

00:06:54.880 --> 00:06:59.279
look to him for energy and for the leadership that they need.

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:03.359
And because of that, he's been a big part of the I believe four

00:07:03.359 --> 00:07:05.720
championships in the last decade that the Golden State Warriors

00:07:05.720 --> 00:07:11.839
have had. So what might be your niche? What could be the thing

00:07:11.839 --> 00:07:14.440
that you're passionate about? And there's many different

00:07:14.440 --> 00:07:17.359
things that it could be many different ideas. I only listed a

00:07:17.359 --> 00:07:20.519
couple here. But one is you could be a subject matter

00:07:20.519 --> 00:07:24.239
expert, there could be a topic in your industry that you're

00:07:24.239 --> 00:07:27.359
very passionate about, or that you really want to learn more

00:07:27.359 --> 00:07:30.640
about and dive into. You might be the only shiny person on your

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:34.160
team, or you really could be the only R person at your company.

00:07:34.559 --> 00:07:37.440
There are many different ways of being a subject matter expert.

00:07:37.839 --> 00:07:41.119
You might be the person that knows everyone that is able to

00:07:41.119 --> 00:07:44.079
bring people together and help them collaborate and

00:07:44.079 --> 00:07:49.079
communicate cross functionally. You might be the person that

00:07:49.079 --> 00:07:51.799
really understands the end to end data workflow and people

00:07:51.799 --> 00:07:57.160
come to you to know what data processes go with what and how

00:07:57.160 --> 00:08:01.200
to navigate those different, different things. You might be

00:08:01.200 --> 00:08:05.880
in a more of a managerial role where you do well in developing

00:08:05.880 --> 00:08:09.160
the careers of others, and organizing teams and helping

00:08:09.160 --> 00:08:13.559
them to collaborate well. But really, it comes down to what is

00:08:13.559 --> 00:08:17.799
your passion? What do you enjoy doing? What is an area of your

00:08:17.799 --> 00:08:22.440
work that you wish you could do more of day to day. And so your

00:08:22.440 --> 00:08:26.679
niche may change over time. And that's okay. And it's important

00:08:26.679 --> 00:08:29.559
to think of what sets you apart, what could you bring to

00:08:29.559 --> 00:08:34.960
the table that's different from others on your team. And the

00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:38.119
third point I wanted to talk about today is advocating for

00:08:38.119 --> 00:08:42.479
yourself, being able to put yourself out there and sell

00:08:42.479 --> 00:08:45.080
yourself, maybe sell the contributions that you're making

00:08:45.080 --> 00:08:50.119
to the company. And for me, this is the most uncomfortable thing

00:08:50.119 --> 00:08:55.359
to do. I don't enjoy talking about my accomplishments and

00:08:55.640 --> 00:09:00.239
trying to push those out there and trying to put myself in

00:09:00.239 --> 00:09:05.559
different areas where I may not feel as comfortable. But I do

00:09:05.559 --> 00:09:10.080
know that it's important for my career development to at least

00:09:10.080 --> 00:09:13.559
advocate for myself in the projects that I want to work on

00:09:13.559 --> 00:09:17.200
in the career path that I want to go. And so it's important for

00:09:17.239 --> 00:09:24.559
me to share that with others. So when I was in grad school, I

00:09:24.559 --> 00:09:27.880
learned a little bit more about how to do this. And so my first

00:09:27.880 --> 00:09:30.880
I was in a two year master's program. And in the first year

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:34.479
of that program, I had a year long career development course.

00:09:34.760 --> 00:09:38.320
So we had a career coach that led us through lectures of resume

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:43.000
development of cover letters, interviewing, networking. And

00:09:43.039 --> 00:09:46.200
one lesson we had was about negotiating. And so one thing

00:09:46.200 --> 00:09:50.359
that she would always say is to know your worth, then ask for

00:09:50.359 --> 00:09:55.080
it. So this had to do with salary negotiation, and not not

00:09:55.080 --> 00:09:59.440
just salary negotiation, but also knowing your the benefits

00:09:59.440 --> 00:10:01.760
that you want and knowing what other at least in my case,

00:10:01.760 --> 00:10:03.960
knowing what other bio statisticians were making and,

00:10:04.119 --> 00:10:08.000
and knowing your worth and being able to ask for it. But we can

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:12.159
also apply this same principle in advocating for yourself at

00:10:12.159 --> 00:10:17.080
work. Know your worth, know what you are capable of not not just

00:10:17.080 --> 00:10:20.840
knowing your worth, but it may be knowing your abilities or

00:10:20.880 --> 00:10:24.880
knowing your aspirations, and then ask for it. Your manager

00:10:24.880 --> 00:10:27.760
may not know everything that you're capable of all of the

00:10:27.760 --> 00:10:30.239
different skills that you have. And they definitely probably

00:10:30.239 --> 00:10:32.960
don't know all of your career aspirations where you want to

00:10:32.960 --> 00:10:36.719
go. And it may be that you don't know yet. And so before you ask

00:10:36.719 --> 00:10:40.239
for it, you have to figure out on your own what abilities you

00:10:40.280 --> 00:10:43.640
have what what or what do you want to learn? And where do you

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:46.280
want to take your your different roles? Where do you want your

00:10:46.280 --> 00:10:49.159
career to go? So once you know that, then you can ask for it.

00:10:51.119 --> 00:10:54.960
So what are different things you might advocate for? I've kind of

00:10:54.960 --> 00:10:57.520
alluded to this already, but maybe you advocate for a new

00:10:57.520 --> 00:11:01.320
project, maybe there is something going on in a

00:11:01.320 --> 00:11:03.799
different department at your work that you want to be a part

00:11:03.799 --> 00:11:07.159
of. Or maybe there's a project that would help you learn a new

00:11:07.159 --> 00:11:10.919
skill that you want to learn. And so you might advocate for a

00:11:10.919 --> 00:11:15.039
new project, you might advocate for sharing your work, hashtag

00:11:15.039 --> 00:11:18.400
open source, sharing what you've developed with, within

00:11:18.400 --> 00:11:20.679
your team within your organization, or just in the

00:11:20.679 --> 00:11:23.840
broader community. You might advocate for more

00:11:23.840 --> 00:11:27.400
responsibility, maybe you reach the point that you feel like you

00:11:27.440 --> 00:11:29.640
have a good grasp of what you're working on, you understand it

00:11:29.640 --> 00:11:33.479
well. And you might advocate for more responsibility. On the

00:11:33.479 --> 00:11:36.039
flip side, you might advocate for less responsibility if you

00:11:36.039 --> 00:11:39.039
feel like you haven't been bogged down too much. And this

00:11:39.039 --> 00:11:42.039
depends on the company, you might not be able to ask for

00:11:42.039 --> 00:11:44.520
less responsibility. But you can advocate for yourself and what

00:11:44.520 --> 00:11:47.919
you what you need. And one other idea is just to advocate

00:11:47.919 --> 00:11:51.039
for personal development. You're all here at PositConf. So you're

00:11:51.039 --> 00:11:54.159
getting personal development here. And you might advocate for

00:11:54.159 --> 00:11:57.479
more of that, or more different aspects of that in your in your

00:11:57.479 --> 00:12:04.799
work. So I've talked about a few different points here about

00:12:04.799 --> 00:12:07.679
expanding your network, finding your niche, advocating for

00:12:07.679 --> 00:12:12.159
yourself. And these can be difficult. And especially for

00:12:12.159 --> 00:12:15.760
me, I've mentioned I'm an introvert. So a lot of these

00:12:15.760 --> 00:12:18.440
have to do with working with people and cloud and

00:12:18.440 --> 00:12:22.400
collaborating and communicating. And it may not be natural for

00:12:23.359 --> 00:12:27.359
data science professionals to, to transition into these areas,

00:12:27.359 --> 00:12:31.000
but they are important to what we want, what we want to

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:35.280
accomplish in our careers. So you might feel like me, and

00:12:35.280 --> 00:12:41.119
especially after the PositConf, like this koala bear, where it's

00:12:41.280 --> 00:12:46.719
it can be uncomfortable to talk to people and especially all day

00:12:46.719 --> 00:12:49.239
and expanding your network and trying to accomplish all these

00:12:49.239 --> 00:12:53.080
goals that you set for yourself. But the thing is just to set

00:12:53.080 --> 00:12:56.760
little goals and see what you can do. And in the long run,

00:12:57.080 --> 00:13:03.880
that's when you can look back and see what you've done. So I

00:13:03.880 --> 00:13:08.840
want to return back to where we began, back to this highly

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:10.880
researched data that I presented to you at the

00:13:10.880 --> 00:13:17.599
beginning, and try to see where it might go for you. Maybe in

00:13:17.599 --> 00:13:23.159
your first year you advocate for yourself and you get onto this

00:13:23.159 --> 00:13:28.039
new project where you learn a skill that later on you're able

00:13:28.039 --> 00:13:31.559
to leverage in a future job interview or in a future project

00:13:31.559 --> 00:13:34.640
at the same company. And then a few years later, you're about

00:13:34.640 --> 00:13:39.039
five years in, you attend an after work social where you set

00:13:39.039 --> 00:13:41.640
a goal for yourself that you're going to talk to one person

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:44.719
before you left that day. So you end up finding someone you talk

00:13:44.719 --> 00:13:48.479
to them, and you find out that there is some overlap in your

00:13:48.479 --> 00:13:52.280
projects and you have you have resources that you can share

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:55.919
between each other. And not only do you have this person that you

00:13:55.919 --> 00:13:59.760
can turn to at your company for a resource, you also have ended

00:13:59.760 --> 00:14:04.039
up making a lifelong friend. And then a few years later, maybe

00:14:04.039 --> 00:14:08.760
10 years into your career, you are able to transition from a

00:14:08.760 --> 00:14:12.280
data role to a project manager or subject matter expert role.

00:14:12.840 --> 00:14:16.840
Because early on in your career, you decided that you really

00:14:16.840 --> 00:14:19.919
wanted to learn about this specific topic in industry and

00:14:19.919 --> 00:14:24.200
you became an expert on this idea. And it ended up years

00:14:24.200 --> 00:14:29.960
later, being an inflection point for you to use that knowledge in

00:14:29.960 --> 00:14:35.119
transitioning roles. So oftentimes, we won't know until

00:14:35.200 --> 00:14:38.679
later on in our career that when we look back, there were these

00:14:38.679 --> 00:14:41.799
different inflection points that led us to where we are today,

00:14:42.159 --> 00:14:47.719
and to see where the career takes us. But it's about putting

00:14:47.719 --> 00:14:52.840
in the little efforts now to see where it takes us. So as I was

00:14:52.840 --> 00:14:57.479
thinking about what I would share today, and also thinking

00:14:57.479 --> 00:15:00.919
back to when I was in school about what a data science career

00:15:00.919 --> 00:15:05.880
would look like, I was thinking about the different technical

00:15:05.880 --> 00:15:09.119
skills that I brought to the table. And I thought those

00:15:09.119 --> 00:15:11.640
technical skills would be the most important thing that I

00:15:11.640 --> 00:15:14.599
brought to a data science career. And while they're very

00:15:14.599 --> 00:15:18.200
important, there's so much more to a data science career, and so

00:15:18.200 --> 00:15:22.919
many things that were unexpected for me, that are very important

00:15:22.960 --> 00:15:27.320
in where a career path takes us. And it all kind of came down to

00:15:27.320 --> 00:15:32.320
the idea that it's not just about the data, it's also about

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:35.200
the people. Thank you.

00:15:45.000 --> 00:15:51.119
All right, caught me off guard. All right, so we have time for

00:15:51.119 --> 00:15:55.239
questions. Sure. Okay. All right. Question number one. How

00:15:55.239 --> 00:15:58.880
do you balance your day to day tasks with work passion projects

00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:02.119
that could benefit the company? And how do you prioritize time

00:16:02.119 --> 00:16:02.640
for that?

00:16:03.679 --> 00:16:09.080
That's a great question. I think for me, it's difficult because

00:16:09.080 --> 00:16:13.200
there are certain projects that have to be done. I mean, there

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:17.679
are different deliverables that you can't just leave aside to

00:16:17.679 --> 00:16:20.799
work on your work passion projects. And I think it's

